summary: The long tail of the great comet visible through the high scuttling clouds. Sansa was watching it from her tower window when Ser...
caption:
The long tail of the great comet visible through the high scuttling clouds. Sansa was watching it from her tower window when Ser Arys Oakheart arrived to escort her down to the tourney grounds. “What do you think it means?” she asked him.

“Glory to your betrothed,” Ser Arys answered at once.[…]  “He is the dragon’s heir “

body:
Protect Your King

Let’s give a shoutout to all the people who have protected Aegon Targaryen, the Sixth of His Name, since the precious bean was born.

First, we have this badass mothafucka right here:

He was gonna PROTECT that baby.

“Our Prince wanted us here.”

So like, fuck off.

Then, we have this hot slice, who probably would have picked up a sword and cut some bitches herself, if she hadn’t been pushing out a human at the time. I don’t think this lady was one with whom you’d want to fuck.

Moving on, next we have good Uncle Ned. He risked himself, his family, and his honor to keep that baby safe.

Thank you, Lord Stark.

And this shit happened really before the main events.

The Lord Protector of the Jon Protection Squad is this precious cinnamon roll:

Like, it’s Sam’s one job.

So who else has saved that fine peach ass over the years?

This old softy

This creepy bitch

Uncle Benjen

And the ladies who really really saved his ass from his own stupidity

Without these people Jon Snow is toast. Let’s thank these people.

summary: What frustrates me so much about Ned as a character is that he's portrayed as this ideal hero/father figure by the fandom and...
question: What frustrates me so much about Ned as a character is that he's portrayed as this ideal hero/father figure by the fandom and the narrative, and yet his actions cause lasting consequences, esp for Jon and Sansa. even theon (taking an innocent hostage, who depends on his father's obedience for survival, to every beheading is fucking cold). And we never see these characters reflect on his issues and their effect on them. Was it even GRRM's intention to make Ned so oblivious and negligent?
answer: I don’t even think GRRM realises or cares that Ned’s not that great. There’s some serious glorification in the books. I bet the Theon ‘my real father died in King’s Landing’ scene will show up in WoW which is fucked up. That man was holding him hostage, allowed him to get beaten by household members and without hesitation would have executed him if Balon rebelled. Sansa won’t think about Ned putting her in danger when he took her to KL while investigating the Lannisters. She’ll feel bad about going to Cersei and betraying gallant Ned (who let’s not forget told Cersei everything). Jon won’t think about how Ned was 100% ok with him joining the Night’s Watch because it makes him less of a threat to Robert. He’ll reject Rhaegar to embrace Ned because Ned is that perfect.

It’s been a year since season 7 and I’m still pissed that the show combined Jon’s story with his brother Aegon. It makes zero fucking sense for Lyanna to name her son Aegon when Rhaegar already had a son with that name?!


Jahaerys Targaryen to keep the J or even Aemon Targaryen(Jon’s favorite knight in the books and the man that made life at the wall bearable) and you choose the name that’s already taken?! Go home D&D, you’re drunk.

tags: Very different choices made by the two characters
Their so called 'metas' are so dumb
summary:
Jonsa logic is very funny.  Robb waged war in the Riverlands
for Northern independence – wreaking havoc on the lives of the...
body:
Jonsa logic is very funny.

Robb waged war in the Riverlands for Northern independence – wreaking havoc on the lives of the smallfolk living there. This was explored by GRRM through his Arya and Brienne chapters where they travel through the war ravaged Riverlands. The ‘Broken Man’ speech in A Feast for Crows is all about this.

Robb executes Rickard Karstark because he kills Lannister prisoners of war in retaliation for Catelyn letting Jaime go free. This angers the Karstarks who leave with their men and join the Boltons against the Starks.

Robb threw away a very valuable alliance for his love for Talisa, a healer. The alliance with the Freys was so important that Catelyn had to promise not only Robb in marriage to a Frey but also Arya - in return for the use of a bridge. Robb shat all over that deal, went back on a promise, married for love and ended up getting himself, his mother, his wife and child killed with Bran and Rickon having to flee WF.

Jon realizes that Northern independence is not the be all and end all of what is important when an existential threat is on it’s way. He sees that Dany is a good person, a powerful ruler who understands that defeating the greater threat is more important than her personal mission. He realizes that allying with her is better than fighting a war against her and bends the knee.

Jon forgives the Karstark and Umber children, despite the sins of their fathers, allowing them to keep their ancestral homes and lands in return for their loyalty to house Stark. Unlike Robb, he makes peace with the Karstarks and brings them back into the Stark fold.

Jon falls in love with the most powerful leader in Westeros and also allies with her by bending the knee. Dany offers to help the North defeat the WW with all her resources and in return Jon offers her the North’s help in defeating Cersei.

Jonsas: Jon is making the same stupid mistakes that Robb did!! That is not Jon’s story!! He is not supposed to be stupid like Robb! He is supposed to be smarter!! And that’s why we came up with the undercover!Jon theory. Because otherwise Jon would be stupid like Robb!!

Even ignoring the above laid out facts where Jon does precisely the opposite of Robb, what do Jonsas think is going to happen once Jon goes up North with Dany? Is Sansa going to arrange a ‘red wedding’ for Jon/Dany? Is Lord Glover – who lost a son in the red wedding – going to betray and stab Jon to death for bending the knee? Where is the time for all this? The WW are literally on their doorstep. The good guys are the people who actually recognize this and put aside their enmities and unite against the common, greater threat.

Also recognize that Catelyn had to promise both Robb and Arya in marriage to a Frey for just the use of a bridge! Jon was asking Dany for all her resources to defend the North…And Stark stans want her to do it for free? lol!

Where is the time for all this? The WW are literally on their doorstep. The good guys are the people who actually recognize this and put aside their enmities and unite against the common, greater threat.

Also recognize that Catelyn had to promise both Robb and Arya in marriage to a Frey for just the use of a bridge! Jon was asking Dany for all her resources to defend the North…And Stark stans want her to do it for free? lol!
